Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

The prices of the stocks of companies listed under a global exchange are influenced by a variety of factors, with the company's financial performance, innovations and collaborations, and market sentiment being factors that play a significant role. News and media reports can rapidly affect investor perceptions and, consequently, stock prices in the highly competitive financial industry. With the sheer volume of news and opinions from a wide variety of sources, investors and financial analysts often struggle to stay updated and accurately interpret its impact on the market. As a result, investment firms need sophisticated tools to analyze market sentiment and integrate this information into their investment strategies.

Problem Definition¶

With an ever-rising number of news articles and opinions, an investment startup aims to leverage artificial intelligence to address the challenge of interpreting stock-related news and its impact on stock prices. They have collected historical daily news for a specific company listed under NASDAQ, along with data on its daily stock price and trade volumes.

As a member of the Data Science and AI team in the startup, you have been tasked with analyzing the data, developing an AI-driven sentiment analysis system that will automatically process and analyze news articles to gauge market sentiment, and summarizing the news at a weekly level to enhance the accuracy of their stock price predictions and optimize investment strategies. This will empower their financial analysts with actionable insights, leading to more informed investment decisions and improved client outcomes.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Date : The date the news was released
  • News : The content of news articles that could potentially affect the company's stock price
  • Open : The stock price (in $) at the beginning of the day
  • High : The highest stock price (in $) reached during the day
  • Low : The lowest stock price (in $) reached during the day
  • Close : The adjusted stock price (in $) at the end of the day
  • Volume : The number of shares traded during the day
  • Label : The sentiment polarity of the news content
    • 1: positive
    • 0: neutral
    • -1: negative

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In [ ]:
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram
In [ ]:
# function to create labeled barplots
def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot
In [ ]:
# Function to get a dominant sentiment based on the news in a given day
def get_dominant_sentiment(series):
    mode = series.mode()
    return mode[0] if not mode.empty else None

Label¶

labeled_barplot(data, 'Label', perc=True)
  • Neutral: The majority of the news articles are labeled as neutral (0), accounting for approximately 48.7% of the dataset.
  • Comparable negative and positive sentiment: The counts for negative (-1) and positive (+1) news articles are relatively similar, representing around 28.4% and 22.9% of the data, respectively.
  • Imbalanced distribution: The distribution is not balanced, with neutral news significantly outnumbering both negative and positive news.

Date¶

labeled_barplot(data, 'Date', perc=False)

  • High variability in news volume: There's a significant disparity in the number of news articles shared per day, ranging from a high of 28 down to days with only one or two articles.

Correlation¶

plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
sns.heatmap(data[numeric_features].corr(),annot=True,vmin=-1,vmax=1,fmt='.2f',cmap="Spectral")
plt.show()
  • Very Strong Positive Correlation: Open, High, Low, and Close prices forthe stock are very strongly correlated.
  • Weak Negative Correlation: Volume has a weak negative correlation with Open, High, Low, and Close prices (correlation around -0.05 to -0.10).
  • Weak Positive Correlation: News_Length with Open, High, Low, and Close prices (correlation around 0.09).
  • Very Weak Correlation: Volume with News_Length (correlation around -0.02).

News Sentiment (Label) vs Price features (Open,Close,High,Low)¶

In [ ]:
# Box Plots for price features against news sentiment
price_features = ['Open', 'Close', 'High', 'Low']
# Copy data to temp df for replacing the Label values
temp_df = data.copy()
# Replace the Label values
temp_df['Label'] = temp_df['Label'].replace({-1: 'Negative', 0: 'Neutral', 1: 'Positive'})

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
for i, feature in enumerate(price_features):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, i + 1)
    sns.boxplot(x='Label', y=feature, data=temp_df)
    plt.title(f'{feature} Price vs. Sentiment')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
  • Days with neutral or positive news showed largely similar price patterns for Open, Close, High, and Low.
  • When the news was negative, all the prices (Open, Close, High, and Low) tended to be a bit lower, and the range during the day was generally smaller.

Train Test Validation Data Split¶

In [ ]:
# Use approximately 70% of the data for training
train_end_date = '2019-03-15' # Mid-March

# Use approximately 15% of the data for validation
val_end_date = '2019-04-04'   # Mid March to first week of April

# Use approximately 15% of the data for testing
test_start_date = '2019-04-05' # End of first week of April till month end

X_train = data[data['Date'] <= train_end_date].reset_index(drop=True)
X_val = data[(data['Date'] > train_end_date) & (data['Date'] <= val_end_date)].reset_index(drop=True)
X_test = data[data['Date'] >= test_start_date].reset_index(drop=True)

print(f"Train set size: {len(X_train)}, Split: {len(X_train)/len(data)* 100:.2f} %")
print(f"Validation set size: {len(X_val)}, Split: {len(X_val)/len(data)* 100:.2f} %")
print(f"Test set size: {len(X_test)}, Split: {len(X_test)/len(data)* 100:.2f} %")

Train set size: 245, Split: 70.20 %
Validation set size: 53, Split: 15.19 %
Test set size: 51, Split: 14.61 %
In [ ]:
# Set the target variable
y_train = X_train['Label']
y_val = X_val['Label']
y_test = X_test['Label']

Word Embeddings¶

Word2Vec¶

  • Word2Vec is imported from Gensim library

  • Word2Vec takes the following important parameters:

    1. word_list: List of all words in all documents
    2. vector_size: Determines the size of the word vectors
    3. min_count: It will ignore all the words with a total frequency lower than this.
    4. Workers: These are the number of threads to train the model.
    5. window: Size of context relative to target word.

  • By default, it creates word vectors of size 100.

In [ ]:
# Creating a list of all words in our data
words_list = [item.split(" ") for item in data['News'].values]
In [ ]:
# Creating an instance of Word2Vec
vec_size = 300
model_W2V = Word2Vec(words_list, vector_size = vec_size, min_count = 1, window=5, workers = 6)
In [ ]:
# Checking the size of the vocabulary
print("Length of the vocabulary is", len(list(model_W2V.wv.key_to_index)))

Length of the vocabulary is 4682

In [ ]:
# Retrieving the words present in the Word2Vec model's vocabulary
words = list(model_W2V.wv.key_to_index.keys())

# Retrieving word vectors for all the words present in the model's vocabulary
wvs = model_W2V.wv[words].tolist()

# Creating a dictionary of words and their corresponding vectors
word_vector_dict = dict(zip(words, wvs))
In [ ]:
def average_vectorizer_Word2Vec(doc):
    # Initializing a feature vector for the sentence
    feature_vector = np.zeros((vec_size,), dtype="float64")

    # Creating a list of words in the sentence that are present in the model vocabulary
    words_in_vocab = [word for word in doc.split() if word in words]

    # adding the vector representations of the words
    for word in words_in_vocab:
        feature_vector += np.array(word_vector_dict[word])

    # Dividing by the number of words to get the average vector
    if len(words_in_vocab) != 0:
        feature_vector /= len(words_in_vocab)

    return feature_vector
In [ ]:
# creating dataframes of the vectorized documents
X_train_wv = pd.DataFrame(X_train['News'].apply(average_vectorizer_Word2Vec).tolist(), columns=['Feature '+str(i) for i in range(vec_size)])
X_val_wv  = pd.DataFrame(X_val['News'].apply(average_vectorizer_Word2Vec).tolist(), columns=['Feature '+str(i) for i in range(vec_size)])
X_test_wv = pd.DataFrame(X_test['News'].apply(average_vectorizer_Word2Vec).tolist(), columns=['Feature '+str(i) for i in range(vec_size)])

In [ ]:
vec_size=100
In [ ]:
def average_vectorizer_GloVe(doc):
    # Initializing a feature vector for the sentence
    feature_vector = np.zeros((vec_size,), dtype="float64")

    # Creating a list of words in the sentence that are present in the model vocabulary
    words_in_vocab = [word for word in doc.split() if word in glove_words]

    # adding the vector representations of the words
    for word in words_in_vocab:
        feature_vector += np.array(glove_word_vector_dict[word])

    # Dividing by the number of words to get the average vector
    if len(words_in_vocab) != 0:
        feature_vector /= len(words_in_vocab)

    return feature_vector

X_val_st  =  model.encode(X_val['News'], device=device, show_progress_bar=True)
X_test_st =  model.encode(X_test['News'], device=device, show_progress_bar=True)

Sentiment Analysis¶

Model evaluation criterion¶

F1-weighted will be a good metric for our Sentiment Analysis, due to the below reasons:-

  • Handles Imbalanced Data by Weighting Sentiments: Our dataset's imbalance, with a higher prevalence of "neutral" news, requires a metric like F1-weighted. It evaluates model performance on each sentiment ("positive," "negative," "neutral") and weights them according to their frequency, providing a more accurate overall assessment.
  • Focuses on All Sentiments: We need to correctly find all types of sentiment, not just the most common one.
  • Balances Mistakes: It checks if the model makes too many wrong guesses of one kind.
  • Good Overall Score: It gives one number that tells us how well the model understands all the different sentiments in our data.

Let's define a function to output different metrics (including f1_score weighted) on the train, validation and test set.

In [ ]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of the model
def model_performance(model, predictors, target,modeldesc=None,word_embedding=None):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check model performance
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors) # Get predicted probabilities

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute weighted Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute weighted Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute weighted F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics along with model description
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Model": modeldesc,
            "Word Embedding": word_embedding,
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [ ]:
# Define dataframe to record the metrics for each of the models
columns = ["Model","Word Embedding","Accuracy","Recall","Precision","F1"]

training_results = pd.DataFrame(columns=columns)
validation_results = pd.DataFrame(columns=columns)
test_results = pd.DataFrame(columns=columns)
In [ ]:
# creating a function to plot the confusion matrix
def plot_confusion_matrix(actual, predicted):
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)

    plt.figure(figsize = (5, 4))
    label_list = ['negative', 'positive']
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True,  fmt = '.0f', xticklabels = label_list, yticklabels = label_list)
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Tuned - Random Forest with Word2Vec¶

In [ ]:
%%time
# show progress

# Choose the type of classifier.
rf1_wv = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {"n_estimators": [100,150,200,250],
    "min_samples_leaf": np.arange(5, 10),
    "max_features": np.arange(0.2, 0.7, 0.1),
    "max_samples": np.arange(0.3, 0.7, 0.1),
    "class_weight" : ['balanced', 'balanced_subsample'],
    "max_depth":np.arange(3,4,5),
    "min_impurity_decrease":[0.001, 0.002, 0.003]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = 'f1_weighted'

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(rf1_wv, parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=5, n_jobs= -1, verbose = 2)
# verbose = 2 tells about the number of fits, which can give an idea of how long will the model take in tuning
# n_jobs = -1 so that all CPU cores can be run parallelly to optimize the Search

grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train_wv, y_train)

# Print the best combination of parameters
grid_obj.best_params_

Model Comparison and Final Model Selection¶

In [ ]:
#Make 'Model' as index

validation_results.set_index('Model',inplace=True)
test_results.set_index('Model',inplace=True)
In [ ]:
training_results
Out[ ]:
Word Embedding Accuracy Recall Precision F1
Model
Random Forest Word2Vec 1.000000 1.000000 1.000000 1.000000
Random Forest Glove 0.995918 0.995918 0.995952 0.995912
Random Forest Sentence Transformer 1.000000 1.000000 1.000000 1.000000
Random Forest - Tuned Word2Vec 0.751020 0.751020 0.755819 0.752285
Random Forest - Tuned Glove 0.759184 0.759184 0.767555 0.760442
Random Forest - Tuned Sentence Transformer 0.885714 0.885714 0.886057 0.885598
  • Overfitting: The base Random Forest models (Word2Vec, GloVe, Sentence Transformer) learned the training data almost perfectly, indicating significant overfitting.
  • Impact of Tuning: The training scores for the Word2Vec model saw the largest drop after tuning (from 1.0 to ~0.75), indicating that tuning had the most significant effect on reducing its training fit. The training scores for the GloVe model dropped from ~0.996 to ~0.760 after tuning.
  • Tuned Sentence Transformer: The tuned Sentence Transformer model still achieved very high scores on the training data, suggesting potential remaining overfitting.

validation_results
Out[ ]:
Word Embedding Accuracy Recall Precision F1
Model
Random Forest Word2Vec 0.471698 0.471698 0.424528 0.413864
Random Forest Glove 0.377358 0.377358 0.338427 0.351101
Random Forest Sentence Transformer 0.471698 0.471698 0.437473 0.411321
Random Forest - Tuned Word2Vec 0.490566 0.490566 0.511321 0.493238
Random Forest - Tuned Glove 0.339623 0.339623 0.343251 0.341274
Random Forest - Tuned Sentence Transformer 0.396226 0.396226 0.360488 0.369353
  • Modest Performance Overall: The validation F1-scores across all models are relatively low, ranging from approximately 0.34 to 0.49, indicating a challenging sentiment analysis task on unseen data.
  • Highest Validation F1: The Tuned Random Forest model with Word2Vec embeddings achieved the highest validation F1-score (around 0.49), suggesting the best generalization among the tested models.
  • Lowest Validation F1: The Tuned Random Forest model with GloVe embeddings exhibits the lowest validation F1-score (around 0.34), indicating the weakest generalization.
  • Impact of Tuning on Generalization: Tuning improved the validation F1-score for Word2Vec, had minimal impact on GloVe, and decreased it for Sentence Transformer.

Final Model¶

Tuned Random Forest model with Word2Vec embeddings is most likely to perform best on completely new, unseen test data compared to the other models evaluated so far. The reasons for the same are listed below:-

  • Highest Validation F1-Score
  • Positive Impact of Tuning
  • Better Generalization Compared to Others

Summarization¶

Note:

  • The model is expected to summarize the news from the week by identifying the top three positive and negative events that are most likely to impact the price of the stock.

  • As an output, the model is expected to return a JSON containing two keys, one for Positive Events and one for Negative Events.

For the project, we need to define the prompt to be fed to the LLM to help it understand the task to perform. The following should be the components of the prompt:

  1. Role: Specifies the role the LLM will be taking up to perform the specified task, along with any specific details regarding the role
  • Example: You are an expert data analyst specializing in news content analysis.
  1. Task: Specifies the task to be performed and outlines what needs to be accomplished, clearly defining the objective
  • Example: Analyze the provided news headline and return the main topics contained within it.
  1. Instructions: Provides detailed guidelines on how to perform the task, which includes steps, rules, and criteria to ensure the task is executed correctly
  • Example:
Instructions:
1. Read the news headline carefully.
2. Identify the main subjects or entities mentioned in the headline.
3. Determine the key events or actions described in the headline.
4. Extract relevant keywords that represent the topics.
5. List the topics in a concise manner.
  1. Output Format: Specifies the format in which the final response should be structured, ensuring consistency and clarity in the generated output
  • Example: Return the output in JSON format with keys as the topic number and values as the actual topic.

Full Prompt Example:

You are an expert data analyst specializing in news content analysis.

Task: Analyze the provided news headline and return the main topics contained within it.

Instructions:
1. Read the news headline carefully.
2. Identify the main subjects or entities mentioned in the headline.
3. Determine the key events or actions described in the headline.
4. Extract relevant keywords that represent the topics.
5. List the topics in a concise manner.

Return the output in JSON format with keys as the topic number and values as the actual topic.

Sample Output:

{"1": "Politics", "2": "Economy", "3": "Health" }

Utility Functions¶
In [ ]:
# defining a function to parse the JSON output from the model
def extract_json_data(json_str):
    import json
    try:
        # Find the indices of the opening and closing curly braces
        json_start = json_str.find('{')
        json_end = json_str.rfind('}')

        if json_start != -1 and json_end != -1:
            extracted_category = json_str[json_start:json_end + 1]  # Extract the JSON object
            data_dict = json.loads(extracted_category)
            return data_dict
        else:
            print(f"Warning: JSON object not found in response: {json_str}")
            return {}
    except json.JSONDecodeError as e:
        print(f"Error parsing JSON: {e}")
        return {}
In [ ]:
# Define a function to split the top 3 events into separate columns
def split_events(df):
    df[['Positive Event 1', 'Positive Event 2', 'Positive Event 3']] = pd.DataFrame(df['Positive Events'].tolist(), index=df.index)
    df[['Negative Event 1', 'Negative Event 2', 'Negative Event 3']] = pd.DataFrame(df['Negative Events'].tolist(), index=df.index)
    # normalise JSON values
    df['Positive Event 1'] = df['Positive Event 1'].apply(lambda x: x['Event'] if isinstance(x, dict) and 'Event' in x else None)
    df['Positive Event 2'] = df['Positive Event 2'].apply(lambda x: x['Event'] if isinstance(x, dict) and 'Event' in x else None)
    df['Positive Event 3'] = df['Positive Event 3'].apply(lambda x: x['Event'] if isinstance(x, dict) and 'Event' in x else None)
    df['Negative Event 1'] = df['Negative Event 1'].apply(lambda x: x['Event'] if isinstance(x, dict) and 'Event' in x else None)
    df['Negative Event 2'] = df['Negative Event 2'].apply(lambda x: x['Event'] if isinstance(x, dict) and 'Event' in x else None)
    df['Negative Event 3'] = df['Negative Event 3'].apply(lambda x: x['Event'] if isinstance(x, dict) and 'Event' in x else None)
    return df.drop(columns=['Positive Events', 'Negative Events'])
Defining the response function¶
In [ ]:
#Defining the response function
def response_mistral_1(prompt, news):
    model_output = llm(
      f"""
      [INST]
      {prompt}
      News Articles: {news}
      [/INST]
      """,
      max_tokens=3000, #Complete the code to set the maximum number of tokens the model should generate for this task.
      temperature=0.01, #Complete the code to set the value for temperature.
      top_p=0.75, #Complete the code to set the value for top_p
      top_k=30, #Complete the code to set the value for top_k
      echo=False,
    )

    final_output = model_output["choices"][0]["text"]

    return final_output

Conclusions and Recommendations¶






















Conclusions






















    

  • News Volume and Sentiment
      

    • Daily news articles ranged from 1 to 28, peaking at 28 on January 3, 2019, indicating high variability in news activity.
      • 

    • Sentiment was 48.7% neutral, 28.4% negative, and 22.9% positive, with neutral sentiment dominating and positive/negative sentiment in shorter cycles.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Price-Sentiment Dynamics
      

    • Stock prices (mean Close: $44.93) typically rose after positive news (e.g., strong earnings) and fell after negative news (e.g., revenue warnings).
      • 

    • Price changes on neutral news days (48.7% of dataset) were likely driven by external factors, such as market events.
      • 

    • Open, High, Low, and Close prices were highly correlated, with stable daily volatility and occasional sharp spikes/dips tied to news or market events.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Trading Volume Patterns
      

    • Trading volume (mean: 128.95M shares) varied widely, with spikes often linked to price jumps or drops, though not always causing price changes.
      • 

    • Neutral news days had the widest volume range, negative news days the narrowest, with high volume more frequent on positive/negative news days.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Sentiment Analysis Model Performance
      

    • Random Forest models (Word2Vec, GloVe, Sentence Transformer) overfit, achieving near-perfect training scores (e.g., Word2Vec: 1.0).
      • 

    • Tuning reduced overfitting (e.g., Word2Vec training score dropped to ~0.75), but validation F1-scores were low (0.34–0.49), and test set performance dropped, confirming poor generalization.
      • 

    • The Tuned Word2Vec model performed best (validation F1: ~0.49).
      • 

    

    • 

  • Weekly News Summarization
      

    • The Mistral LLM generated JSON summaries, identifying the top three positive and negative events weekly (e.g., earnings, revenue warnings).
      • 

    • Summaries effectively captured stock price-relevant events, despite variable news volume and sentiment shifts.
      • 

    

    • 























Recommendations






















    

  • Enhance Sentiment Analysis
      

    • Implement advanced models (e.g., transformers) and train on larger, balanced datasets to reduce overfitting and improve F1-scores (0.34–0.49).
      • 

    • Optimize tuning for GloVe and Sentence Transformer to further reduce overfitting and enhance test set performance, building on Word2Vec’s success.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Improve News Summarization and Analysis
      

    • Refine the Mistral LLM prompt to prioritize high-impact events in JSON outputs, ensuring concise and accurate summaries.
      • 

    • Validate summaries against price movements and quantify price changes after positive/negative news to strengthen sentiment-price models.
      • 

    • Investigate external factors driving price movements on neutral news days (48.7% of dataset).
      • 

    

    • 

  • Develop Robust Predictive Models
      

    • Build hybrid models combining sentiment scores, weekly summary events, news volume, and trading volume to predict prices, leveraging strong price correlations.
      • 

    • Incorporate additional features like macroeconomic indicators, news length, and market events, focusing on neutral news days and sharp price movements.
      • 

    • Backtest models with historical price data to ensure reliability and address test set performance issues for real-world applicability.
      • 

    

    • 























Power Ahead
